 taking material “from all sources, experience, report, and the records of human affairs,” each contributor examines within the contexts of their time and historical traditions the anxieties and imperatives of the auto/biographer as she or he shapes material into a legacy. New work on Frances Burney D’Arblay’s son, Alexander, as revealed through letters; on Isabelle de Charriere; on Hester Thrale Piozzi; and on Alicia LeFanu and Frances Burney’s realignment of family biography extend current conversations about eighteenth century biography and autobiography. Published by Bucknell University Press. Distributed worldwide by Rutgers University Press.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aAutobiography in literature. 0aAutobiographyxHistoryy18th century. 0aBiography as a literary formxHistoryy18th century. 0aBiography in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aBerglund, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerglund, Lisa.1 aCaldwell, Tanya M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaldwell, Tanya M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCaudle, James J.1 aCaudle, James J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrancus, Marilyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrancus, Marilyn.1 aGilman, Todd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilman, Todd.1 aSabor, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSabor, Peter.1 aWarren, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWarren, Victoria.40uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978168448230640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781684482306423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781684482306.jpg  aEB